## Styling Text and Fonts with CSS

CSS provides a wide range of properties to customize the appearance of text on a web page. Here are some of the most commonly used properties:

### Font Family
* Specifies the font family to be used for the text.
* Example: `font-family: Arial, sans-serif;`

### Font Size
* Sets the size of the text.
* Example: `font-size: 24px;`

### Font Weight
* Controls the boldness of the text.
* Example: `font-weight: bold;` or `font-weight: 700;`

### Text Align
* Specifies the horizontal alignment of the text.
* Example: `text-align: center;` or `text-align: right;`

### Other Text Properties
* **Color:** `color: red;`
* **Text Decoration:** `text-decoration: underline;`
* **Line Height:** `line-height: 1.5;`
* **Text Transform:** `text-transform: uppercase;`
* **Letter Spacing:** `letter-spacing: 2px;`

### Example HTML and CSS

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Text and Font Styling</title>
    <style>
        h1 {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            font-size: 36px;
            font-weight: bold;
            text-align: center;
        }

        p {
            font-size: 18px;
            line-height: 1.5;
        }

        a {
            color: blue;
            text-decoration: underline;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>This is a Heading</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
    <p>This is another paragraph.</p>
    <p>Visit <a href="https://example.com">this link</a>.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

This example demonstrates how to style different text elements using CSS. The `h1` element has a larger font size, bold weight, and is centered. The paragraphs have a smaller font size and line height. The link has a blue color and an underline.

By combining these properties, you can create a wide variety of text styles to match the design of your web page.